<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAUNA SNOW and BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, 
national and international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Tomorrow for 'Annie 2'?: In the wake of negative reviews and an equally 
negative audience response at the Kennedy Center in Washington last week, it's 
clear that "Annie 2," the $7-million sequel to the Broadway hit, "Annie," is in 
deep trouble. Reached by telephone at his Washington hotel over the weekend, 
co-producer Roger S. Berlind declined to talk about the show, but he said that 
he and his associates were meeting around the clock. 
</P>
<P>
Playwright and Dramatists Guild president Peter Stone, a Broadway veteran, went 
to Washington last week with directors Tommy Tune and Mike Nichols to offer 
their opinions on how the production might be saved. Stone says he, Tune and 
Nichols went simply as friends and will play no role in doctoring the musical. 
Stone refused any comment on the show's problems, but he acknowledged that its 
producers are "fighting for their lives" and added that the show has no chance 
of surviving on any lingering popularity of "Annie" if it can't stand on its 
own merits. The production is scheduled to open in New York in March. SHAUNA 
SNOW and BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
