<P>
January 15, 1990, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 3; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
376 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: BUENA PARK; 
</P>
<P>
ATTRACTING BUSINESS TOPS CITY'S AGENDA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBORAH CARPENTIER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Encouraging redevelopment, balancing the budget and working to enhance air 
safety are the major concerns facing Buena Park in 1990, Mayor Donald L. Bone 
says. 
</P>
<P>
"We would like to finish the master plan for redevelopment," Bone said in a 
recent interview. "Although much of the plan was completed last year, there are 
still some i's to dot and t's to cross." 
</P>
<P>
Bone said one of the biggest challenges is completion of "Auto Row," a string 
of dealerships on Manchester Avenue at the Santa Ana Freeway. City officials 
also hope to attract more new businesses to the city's entertainment corridor 
along Beach Boulevard, which now includes Knott's Berry Farm and the Movieland 
Wax Museum. 
</P>
<P>
Bone said planning is under way for expanding redevelopment areas, possibly to 
include the Buena Park Mall. Planners are also analyzing the potential 
development of a 300,000-square-foot office building on Orangethorpe, next to 
the Sequoia Athletic Club. 
</P>
<P>
The city might revive a lapsed program offering low-interest loans to city 
business owners who want to expand or improve, Bone said. 
</P>
<P>
Air safety will continue to be a concern at Fullerton Municipal Airport, which 
borders Buena Park, Bone said. Several incidents in the past year, including a 
crash last fall in a Buena Park neighborhood, have led to clashes between 
political leaders of the two cities, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Buena Park leaders will try to "identify common concerns about the airport and 
the crashes that have occurred recently," Bone said. "This situation has caused 
relations to be somewhat tense. My goal is to relax that tenseness and find a 
common ground." 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps most immediate is the city's effort to eliminate a budget deficit, Bone 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The budget for the current fiscal year, ending in June, is $35 million, with a 
projected deficit of more than $700,000. Salary increases for police and 
firefighters have increased that gap, Bone said. 
</P>
<P>
"When you look at the figures, you see one year," said Bone. "If you project 
out and look at two and three years downstream, that's where we begin to come 
into problems." 
</P>
<P>
This month, planning for next year's budget will begin in earnest. 
</P>
<P>
Bone said he expects "a thorough review of our fiscal policies and how we spend 
our money." DEBORAH CARPENTIER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Donald L. Bone 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
