<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOVIET JEWS SEEN NEEDING LAND IN GAZA, WEST BANK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TEL AVIV 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Sunday that Israel has to hold on to the 
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip for a mass wave of Jewish immigration from 
the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
Government officials predict that at least 300,000 Soviet Jews will move to 
Israel in the next three years as a result of new Soviet emigration policies 
and new U.S. restrictions on immigration. 
</P>
<P>
Shamir said the sudden influx of Soviet Jews proves time is on Israel's side 
and will change the face of the Jewish state, making it "bigger, better and 
stronger." 
</P>
<P>
"The Arabs around us are embarrassed. They are in a mood of defeat, stricken 
with fear," the 74-year-old leader told members of his right-wing Likud Party. 
</P>
<P>
"They see the success of Zionism and they have no answer for it. They have no 
cure. We have an answer, and of course it is not a Palestinian state. For the 
big immigration, we must have the land of Israel and we have to fight for it, 
struggle for it." 
</P>
<P>
Asked later if the government will settle Soviet Jews in the occupied 
territories, site of a 25-month-old Palestinian uprising, he told reporters: 
</P>
<P>
"We will need a lot of room to absorb everyone, and every immigrant will go 
where he wants." 
</P>
<P>
Shamir's statements launched his campaign to defeat three hard-line Likud 
ministers challenging him for retracting the dismissal of Science Minister Ezer 
Weizman over alleged contacts with the Palestine Liberation Organization. 
</P>
<P>
Trade Minister Ariel Sharon, architect of Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon, 
Housing Minister David Levy and Economics Minister Yitzhak Modai forced Shamir 
to convene Likud's central committee early next month. 
</P>
<P>
Shamir said: "Everything is about to change here. With all the waves of 
immigration that will come . . . the state will be different, will look 
different. In another five or 10 years, we will not know it." 
</P>
<P>
About 70,000 Jewish settlers now live among the 1.7 million Palestinians in the 
occupied territories. Israeli rightists say mass immigration can help change 
the demographic balance there, strengthening Israel's presence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
