<HEADLINE>
<P>
COSTAS SICK, BUT ENBERG DOES IT ALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LARRY STEWART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NBC's Dick Enberg was pressed into double duty Sunday when Bob Costas came down 
with a severe case of the flu. 
</P>
<P>
Costas was so sick Sunday morning that he checked himself into a Denver 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
Enberg, besides calling the game, also had to take Costas' place on the pregame 
and postgame shows. 
</P>
<P>
Then Ralph Wiley, who was scheduled to conduct postgame interviews in the 
Cleveland locker room, was stricken with the flu during the game. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Donovan, who does play-by-play for NBC on a part-time basis and works for 
the NBC affiliate in Cleveland, filled in for Wiley. 
</P>
<P>
Donovan fared better than O.J. Simpson, who could not remember Denver running 
back Sammy Winder's name during a postgame interview with quarterback John 
Elway. 
</P>
<P>
"Talk us through this touchdown pass to James Wa, Wa . . . Winder," Simpson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"Who's it to?" Elway said. 
</P>
<P>
During his interview of Michael Young, Simpson congratulated the former Bruin 
and Ram on his 60-yard touchdown reception. It was 70 yards. LARRY STEWART 
</P>
</TEXT>
