<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
$1-BILLION U.S. CO-OP VENTURE TO MAKE COMPUTER CHIPS FOLDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A high-flying U.S. venture to regain control of the vital computer chip 
industry from Japanese dominance folded today because it failed to attract 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Clara-based U.S. Memories Inc. was hailed as a $1-billion cooperative 
venture by American companies, but in its seven brief months of life it failed 
to make a single computer chip or earn a single dollar. 
</P>
<P>
"I am extremely disappointed by this turn of events," Sanford L. Kane, 
president of U.S. Memories, said at a news conference. "What happens today does 
not bode well for an industry that has made a technical decision rather than a 
tactical one." 
</P>
<P>
Kane told the crowded news conference that the joint venture will be 
"terminated," largely because of a lack of support from the electronics 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
The venture had not found a new investor since its formation last June by seven 
big-name backers -- International Business Machines Corp., Digital Equipment 
Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co., Intel Corp., Advanced Micro Devices Inc., National 
Semiconductor Corp. and LSI Logic, according to published reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
