<P>
MOTLEY CRUE STAYS ON WAGON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guitars are still thrashed and arenas trashed, but one thing has changed on 
Motley Crue's latest tour: The heavy metal bad boys remember what they do. 
</P>
<P>
"We only remember bits of past tours," lead singer Vince Neil said in this 
week's People magazine. 
</P>
<P>
Booze, drugs and more drugs left the band members' memories as fuzzy as their 
guitar sound, until bassist Nikki Sixx nearly died of a heroin overdose in 
1987. 
</P>
<P>
The entire Crue checked into a drug rehabilitation program, and now a drug 
counselor follows them around on tour to help them stay on the wagon, the 
magazine said. 
</P>
<P>
But concert-goers haven't yet mistaken the group for advocates of temperance. 
</P>
<P>
"We don't just play rock 'n' roll, we live it," Sixx said. "We go on tour and 
get broken bones, diseases, the crowd leaves bloody. It's more like going to 
war." 
</P>
</TEXT>
