THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
TOMBA GETS OK TO RESUME SKIING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MILAN, Italy 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Italy's No. 1 skier Alberto Tomba, who has been out with a fractured 
collarbone, was given medical clearance today and could return to the slopes in 
the World Cup slalom Sunday in Kitzbuehel, Austria. 
</P>
<P>
Tomba, a slalom specialist, was hurt in a spill during a super-giant slalom 
race in Val d'Isere last month. 
</P>
<P>
Tomba has not said if he will continue to compete in Super-G races, a 
combination of downhill speed and giant slalom technique. 
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old skier, who won one slalom race this season before being 
sidelined, is 15th in the World Cup overall standings with 46 points. Leader 
Pirmin Zurbriggen of Switzerland has 166 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
