<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIM CONWAY WINS TURF HONOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Actor Tim Conway, a mainstay on the long-running Carol Burnett show and the 
bumbling Ensign Parker on "McHale's Navy," was elected 1989 Big Sport of 
Turfdom for his part in founding the Don MacBeth Memorial Jockey Fund. 
</P>
<P>
The MacBeth fund was started in 1987 and named for the late jockey, who died of 
cancer in March of that year. 
</P>
<P>
Since that time, it has funded physical therapy and medical treatment and 
provided financial assistance to jockeys in need. 
</P>
<P>
Conway, 54, who got into racing as an exercise rider for his father at old 
Randall Park in Cleveland, is one of several celebrities who have been honored 
by the Turf Publicists of America. Others include composer Burt Bacharach and 
actors Telly Savalas, Jack Klugman and John Forsythe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
